# Summary

<div class="block">

![Radius of Convergence (White)](/img/graphs/complex/radius-of-convergence.png)

A **power series about $a$** is a series of the form $$ \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} c_n(x-a)^n = c_0 + c_1(x-a) + c_2(x-a)^2 + \cdots $$
where $x$ is a variable and the $c_n$'s are constants called the **coefficients** of the series.
For a given power series $\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} c_n(x-a)^n$, there are only three possibilities:

1. The series converges only when $x = a$.
2. The series converges for all $x$.
3. There is a positive number $R$ such that the series converges if $|x-a| < R$ and diverges if $|x-a| > R$.

$R$ in item (3) is called the **radius of convergence**, which is $0$ in case (1) and $\infty$ in case (2) by convention.

