# Term-by-Term
    
If the power series $\sum c_n(x-a)^n$ has radius of convergence $R > 0$, then the function $f$ defined by
$$ f(x) = c_0 + c_1(x-a) + c_2(x-a)^2 + \cdots = \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} c_n(x-a)^n $$ 
satisfy the following on the interval $(a-R, a+R)$:

1. *Differentiation:* $$ f'(x) = c_1 + 2c_2(x-a) + 3c_3(x-a)^2 + \cdots = \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} nc_n(x-a)^{n-1}. $$
2. *Integration:* 
   $$ \int f(x)dx = C + c_0(x-a) + c_1\frac{(x-a)^2}{2} + c_2\frac{(x-a)^3}{3} + \cdots 
                  = C + \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}c_n\frac{(x-a)^{n+1}}{n+1}.
   $$

The radii of convergence (though not necessarily the interval of convergence) of the power series in (1) and (2) are both $R$.
Note this does not explain the properties at the endpoints of the interval.

